This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as it focuses on analyzing sentiment and information flow in online social networks. It could also belong to cs.SD (Software Engineering) as it involves the development of tools to collect and analyze data from social media. Additionally, it could be categorized under cs.CY (Computers and Society) as it discusses the implications of social media on public health. The paper also touches on topics related to cs.SOC (Social Computing) as it analyzes social networks and their impact on behavior. Finally, it could be categorized under cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) as it involves the use of technology to study and improve public health outcomes.
